AGI - New trouble for former Brazilian president, Jair Bolsonaro>, now accused of spending two nights in February at the Hungarian embassy in Brasilia>. According to the New York Times, which revealed the stay, supporting the news with video surveillance images, the former leader of the far right was "hidden" to escape justice. Four days before, on February 8, the judges of the superior court, holders of the investigations to the charge of the former leader, had seized his passport and had told him not to leave Brazil >. "Fake news," said his lawyers in a statement that their client was "hosted for two days" at the embassy of a "friend country".
&nbsp;
According to the lawyers, Bolsonaro would go there "on invitation" of the Hungarian authorities, with the sole purpose of "discussing the political context of the two countries". The video surveillance images published by the New York Times show former president entering the Hungarian embassy on the evening of 12 February and leaving on the 14th in the afternoon. Yesterday evening the Brazilian Ministry of Foreign Affairs asked for "explainations on the arrangement of the former president", and the Hungarian ambassador spent twenty minutes at the headquarters of Brazilian diplomacy, according to a government source of Brasilia. Meanwhile, the judge of the Federal Supreme Court, Alexandre de Moraes, granted the former president a "48-hour term" to explain, told the Afp several judicial sources.
&nbsp;
The former right-wing leader intended "to flee for fear of being tried for his crimes, > to be condemned and imprisoned", accused Gleisi Hoffmann, president of the Lula Workers' Party on social networks. A member of the same party, Lindbergh Farias, has even announced that he has contacted the Office of the Attorney General of the Republic to request the "preventive prison" of Bolsonaro. "This stay in the embassy suggests that the former president was trying to take advantage of his friendship with another far-right leader to escape the Brazilian judicial system," said the MP. In their press release, the lawyers of Jair Bolsonaro recalled that "it is known that the former president has a good relationship with the Hungarian Prime Minister".
&nbsp;
Declared unsuitable last June for spreading false information about the Brazilian electronic urn system, Bolsonaro, 69 years old, saw the judiciary clinging after his defeat against Lula. Last week the federal police recommended his referral to trial in a case of falsification of vaccination certificates against Covid-19. The former leader is also in the view of justice for the alleged undue appropriation of gifts received from foreign countries, including jewels offered by Saudi Arabia.&nbsp;
